nd","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thornton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places throughout England and Scotland so called, from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The placename is most frequent in northern England, especially Yorkshire, where there are at least 16 possible sources for the surname.","Irish: Anglicized (translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Sceachán</i>’ (see   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thorton","meanings":["(1997: 465;2007: 2025; 2010: NA)","English: probably a shortened form of   Thornton  , or a habitational name from Thorton in Marnhull, Dorset, which has the same origin."]},{"name":"Skehan","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> or <b>Ó Sceacháin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Sceachán</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>sceach</i> ‘briar, thorn bush’. The Gaelic name has sometimes been ‘translated’ as   Thornton  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Baroness Margaret Thornton was born about 1341, in Swettenham, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Baron William Golberne."},"et":{"about 1341–":"umbes 1341–Surnud","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","1363–1393":"1363–1393","1341–Female":"1341–Surnud","1337":"1337","1363":"1363","1341":"1341","1393":"1393","about 1341":"umbes 1341","Swettenham,Cheshire,England.":"Swettenham, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Woodley, Cheshire, England":"Woodley, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1341–":"noin 1341–Kuollut","1337–Male":"1337–Kuollut","1363–1393":"1363–1393","1341–Female":"1341–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1363":"1363","1341":"1341","1393":"1393","about 1341":"noin 1341","Swettenham,Cheshire,England.":"Swettenham, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Woodley, Cheshire, England":"Woodley, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1341–":"environ 1341–Décédée","1337–Male":"1337–Décédé","1363–1393":"1363–1393","1341–Female":"1341–Décédée","1337":"1337","1363":"1363","1341":"1341","1393":"1393","about 1341":"environ 1341","Swettenham,Cheshire,England.":"Swettenham, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Woodley, Cheshire, England":"Woodley, Cheshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Baroness Margaret Thornton est née environ 1341, à Swettenham, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Baron William Golberne."},"de":{"about 1341–":"um 1341–Verstorben","1337–Male":"1337–Verstorben","1363–1393":"1363–1393","1341–Female":"1341–Verstorben","1337":"1337","1363":"1363","1341":"1341","1393":"1393","about 1341":"um 1341","Swettenham,Cheshire,England.":"Swettenham, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Woodley, Cheshire, England":"Woodley, Cheshire, England","lifeSummary":"Baroness Margaret Thornton wurde um 1341 in Swettenham, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hatte mit Baron William Golberne mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1341–":"about 1341–Desede","1337–Male":"1337–Desede","1363–1393":"1363–1393","1341–Female":"1341–Desede","1337":"1337","1363":"1363","1341":"1341","1393":"1393","about 1341":"about 1341","Swett